          <span class="suffix">$</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="input-group">
        <label for="yearsToGrow">Years to Grow</label>
        <div class="input-wrapper">
          <input type="number" id="yearsToGrow" value="30" min="1" max="60" step="1">
          <span class="suffix">Yrs</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="calc-result">
        <span class="calc-result-label">Future Portfolio Value</span>
        <div class="calc-result-value" id="futureValueResult">$383,393</div>
        <p style="margin-top: 1rem; font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--text-secondary);">
          Total Contributed: <span id="totalContributed">$91,000</span><br>
          Total Profit: <span id="totalProfit" style="color: var(--accent-color);">$292,393</span>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <script>
      // Calculator Logic
      function initCalculator() {
        const initialInvestmentInput = document.getElementById('initialInvestment');
        const monthlyContributionInput = document.getElementById('monthlyContribution');
        const yearsToGrowInput = document.getElementById('yearsToGrow');

        const futureValueResult = document.getElementById('futureValueResult');
        const totalContributedResult = document.getElementById('totalContributed');
        const totalProfitResult = document.getElementById('totalProfit');

        if (!initialInvestmentInput || !futureValueResult) return;

        function calculate() {
          const principal = parseFloat(initialInvestmentInput.value) || 0;
          const monthly = parseFloat(monthlyContributionInput.value) || 0;
          const years = parseFloat(yearsToGrowInput.value) || 0;

          // Assume 8% annual return, compounded monthly
          const annualRate = 0.08;
          const monthlyRate = annualRate / 12;
          const totalMonths = years * 12;

          // Compound Interest Formula for Principal
          const principalGrowth = principal * Math.pow(1 + monthlyRate, totalMonths);

          // Future Value of a Series Formula for Monthly Contributions
          let contributionGrowth = 0;
          if (monthlyRate > 0) {
            contributionGrowth = monthly * ((Math.pow(1 + monthlyRate, totalMonths) - 1) / monthlyRate);
          } else {
            contributionGrowth = monthly * totalMonths;
          }

          const totalFutureValue = principalGrowth + contributionGrowth;
          const totalContributed = principal + (monthly * totalMonths);
          const totalProfit = totalFutureValue - totalContributed;

          // Format currency
          const formatter = new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', {
            style: 'currency',
            currency: 'USD',
            maximumFractionDigits: 0
          });

          futureValueResult.textContent = formatter.format(totalFutureValue);
          totalContributedResult.textContent = formatter.format(totalContributed);
          totalProfitResult.textContent = formatter.format(totalProfit);
        }

        // Add real-time event listeners
        initialInvestmentInput.addEventListener('input', calculate);
        monthlyContributionInput.addEventListener('input', calculate);
        yearsToGrowInput.addEventListener('input', calculate);

        // Initial calculation
        calculate();
      }

      // Initialize on load and on Astro view transitions
      document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', initCalculator);
      document.addEventListener('astro:page-load', initCalculator);
      if (document.readyState !== 'loading') initCalculator();
    </script>

    <h2>8. Pros, Cons, and Common Misconceptions</h2>

    <p>Investing in the stock market isn't a magical risk-free money printer. It's important to understand the realities of what you're signing up for.</p>

    <h3>The Pros</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Historically High Returns:</strong> The stock market is arguably the greatest wealth-creation tool ever invented, historically outpacing inflation, bonds, and savings accounts.</li>
      <li><strong>Liquidity:</strong> Unlike real estate, where selling a house takes months, you can sell your stocks and have cash in your account in a matter of days.</li>
      <li><strong>Passive Income:</strong> Many companies pay dividends—a portion of their profits distributed directly to shareholders in cash. If you own enough dividend-paying stocks, you can literally get paid just for owning them.</li>
      <li><strong>Low Barrier to Entry:</strong> With fractional shares, anyone can start investing today with $5.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>The Cons</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Volatility:</strong> Your portfolio will fluctuate daily. Watching your net worth drop by thousands of dollars during a bad week is psychologically incredibly difficult.</li>
      <li><strong>Risk of Loss:</strong> If you invest in terrible companies that go bankrupt, or if you panic-sell during a crash, you can and will lose money.</li>
      <li><strong>It Takes Time:</strong> The stock market is not a get-rich-quick scheme. It is a get-rich-slowly scheme. The massive gains you see from compound interest generally happen in decades 2 and 3 of your investing journey.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Common Misconceptions</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><em>"You need thousands of dollars to start."</em> False. Fractional shares allow you to buy slices of expensive stocks. If a stock costs $3,000, you can buy $10 worth of it.</li>
      <li><em>"It's just gambling."</em> False. Day-trading volatile meme stocks or options is gambling. Buying and holding an index fund of the 500 largest, most profitable businesses in America for 30 years is ownership and capitalism at work.</li>
      <li><em>"I need to constantly check my portfolio."</em> False. The best investors often check their portfolios maybe once or twice a year. The more you check, the more likely you are to make an emotional, irrational decision.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>9. What Experienced Investors Know That Beginners Don't</h2>

    <p>If you take away nothing else from this guide, remember this fundamental truth that separates the amateurs from the professionals: <strong>Your biggest enemy in investing is not the market. Your biggest enemy is yourself.</strong></p>

    <p>Experienced investors understand that human psychology is hardwired to do exactly the wrong thing in the stock market. We are evolutionarily programmed to run away from danger (selling during a crash) and run toward safety/crowds (buying at the absolute top of a bubble when everyone else is buying).</p>

    <p>To be successful, you must build a system that prevents you from self-sabotaging. Automate your investments so money is pulled from your checking account and invested on a schedule without you having to click a button. Stop obsessing over daily financial news headlines that are designed to generate clicks through fear. And most importantly, focus on your "time horizon." If you don't need this money for 20 years, who cares what the market does next Tuesday?</p>

    <p>Start small, stay disciplined, buy broad-market index funds, and let time do the heavy lifting. You can explore deeper concepts like the <a href="/average-stock-market-return">average stock market return</a> or dive into specialized tools like a <a href="/stock-split-calculator">stock split calculator</a> later, but for now, the most important step is simply getting started.</p>

    <div class="faq-section">
