      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary style="font-size: 1.15rem; font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); cursor: pointer; list-style-position: inside;">How much money do I need to start investing in stocks?</summary>
        <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">Thanks to fractional shares and zero-commission brokers, you can start investing with as little as $5 or $10. You no longer need thousands of dollars to buy a single share of expensive companies like Amazon or Alphabet.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary style="font-size: 1.15rem; font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); cursor: pointer; list-style-position: inside;">What is the best way for a beginner to start investing?</summary>
        <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">The most effective approach for beginners is to open a brokerage account, fund it, and invest in broad-market index funds like an S&P 500 ETF (e.g., VOO or SPY). This provides instant diversification and lowers risk compared to picking individual stocks.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary style="font-size: 1.15rem; font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); cursor: pointer; list-style-position: inside;">Can I lose all my money in the stock market?</summary>
        <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">If you invest in a single company that goes bankrupt, you can lose your entire investment. However, if you invest in a diversified index fund like the S&P 500, the chance of losing all your money is effectively zero, as it would mean the top 500 U.S. companies all went bankrupt simultaneously.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary style="font-size: 1.15rem; font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); cursor: pointer; list-style-position: inside;">How do beginners actually buy stocks?</summary>
        <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">To buy a stock, you need to open an account with a brokerage (like Fidelity, Schwab, or Robinhood), link your bank account, deposit funds, search for the stock's ticker symbol, enter the amount you want to buy, and place a market or limit order.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary style="font-size: 1.15rem; font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); cursor: pointer; list-style-position: inside;">Is investing in stocks better than saving money in a bank?</summary>
        <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">Over the long term, yes. While bank savings accounts offer safety, their interest rates rarely beat inflation. The stock market has historically returned around 10% annually on average, making it a powerful tool for building wealth over decades.</p>
      </details>
